Q.2 Introduction to Software composition analysis (SCA) - security case study.?" [15M]
Definition:
•	SCA (Software Composition Analysis) is the process of scanning software to identify third-party and open-source components, detect vulnerabilities, and ensure license compliance.
Case Study – Fintech Application:
•	Scenario: A mobile banking app uses several third-party libraries for payments, encryption, and analytics.
•	Problem: One library contains a known vulnerability that could allow attackers to steal sensitive data.
Implementation of SCA:
1.	Inventory Management: List all third-party and open-source components.
2.	Vulnerability Detection: Use SCA tools like Snyk, WhiteSource, or Black Duck to detect known issues.
3.	License Compliance: Verify that open-source libraries comply with licensing policies.
4.	Remediation: Patch or replace vulnerable libraries before deployment.
5.	Continuous Monitoring: Track new vulnerabilities after deployment and update dependencies as needed.
Outcome:
•	Prevented data breaches and financial fraud.
•	Ensured regulatory compliance with PCI DSS, PSD2, RBI PSS.
•	Increased customer trust and software security.
Conclusion:
•	SCA is essential in fintech for secure, compliant, and reliable software delivery.









